- Why personal projects matter

Technology was never the goal.

The goal was: To understand well enough that I can build something of my own.

I'm not learning a framework. I'm learning to solve a problem.

Every time I learn a new technology, I try to build a personal project.

Not because I need another app.

But because I've noticed that I truly learn only when I have to make the decisions myself.

A course shows you how an API works.

A personal project forces you to answer questions the course never asks:
- What models do I need?
- What's the simplest data structure?
- What actually matters, and what can wait?
- How do I want the user experience to feel?

That's the moment technology stops being the goal.

It becomes just a tool.

And the real challenge is to build something that makes sense.


-------  A personal project doesn't validate what I learned. It reveals what I still don't understand.----------
